<div class="journal-entry-wrapper post-text authored-by-baratunde ">
<div id="item14600958" class="journal-entry">

  <div class="journal-entry-float-day"><span class="name">Monday</span></div><div class="journal-entry-float-date"><span class="month">Jan</span><span class="date">16</span><span class="year">2012</span></div>
  
  
  
  <div class="journal-entry-text">
  
      
      <h2 class="title">
    
        
    
        <a class="journal-entry-navigation-current" href="/blog/2012/1/16/my-annual-mlk-internet-tradition-spiritual-death-and-twitter.html">My annual MLK Internet tradition: Spiritual Death and&nbsp;Twitter</a>  
     
         
    
      </h2>
      
       <div class="journal-entry-tag journal-entry-tag-post-title"><span class="posted-on">   <img title="Date" alt="Date" class="inline-icon date-icon" rel="dark" src="/universal/images/transparent.png" />Monday, January 16, 2012 at 10:26</span> |  <span class="posted-by">  <a href="/blog/author/baratunde"> <img title="Author" alt="Author" class="inline-icon user-registered-icon" rel="dark" src="/universal/images/transparent.png" />baratunde</a></span> |  <span class="tagged-with">tagged <span class="tag-element"><a rel="tag" href="/blog/tag/dr-martin-luther-king-jr"> <img title="Tag" alt="Tag" class="inline-icon tag-icon" rel="dark" src="/universal/images/transparent.png" />Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.</a></span>, <span class="tag-element"><a rel="tag" href="/blog/tag/mlk"> <img title="Tag" alt="Tag" class="inline-icon tag-icon" rel="dark" src="/universal/images/transparent.png" />MLK</a></span>, <span class="tag-element"><a rel="tag" href="/blog/tag/mlk-day"> <img title="Tag" alt="Tag" class="inline-icon tag-icon" rel="dark" src="/universal/images/transparent.png" />MLK Day</a></span>, <span class="tag-element"><a rel="tag" href="/blog/tag/twitter"> <img title="Tag" alt="Tag" class="inline-icon tag-icon" rel="dark" src="/universal/images/transparent.png" />Twitter</a></span>, <span class="tag-element"><a rel="tag" href="/blog/tag/youtube"> <img title="Tag" alt="Tag" class="inline-icon tag-icon" rel="dark" src="/universal/images/transparent.png" />YouTube</a></span></span>  </div> 

    
  
      
      <div class="body">
  
        
        
        
          <p>Two years ago, YouTube's News &amp; Politics channel sponsored a program encouraging people to read passages from Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s life. I chose a passage from <a href="http://mlk-kpp01.stanford.edu/index.php/encyclopedia/encyclopedia/enc_beyond_vietnam_4_april_1967/">his "Beyond Vietnam" speech</a> on budget/defense priorities and "spiritual death" and recorded <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYaYDWc1J0o">the video</a> at a parking lot in Pittsburgh, PA.</p>
<p><iframe width="640" height="360" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/YYaYDWc1J0o" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>In the same year, Vanity Fair commissioned me to write this piece. It ranks high among the work I'm most proud of across my entire life: <a href="http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2010/01/thurston">What Would MLK Make Of Twitter?</a>&nbsp;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>At this time every year, commentators across the United States engage in an exercise I&rsquo;ll call Hypothetical King, in which we try to imagine what Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. would say about the war in Afghanistan, the bank bailouts, or Mo&rsquo;Nique winning best supporting actress for Precious at the Golden Globes. We extrapolate from his words and deeds and hope we&rsquo;re right but can never be sure.</p>
<p>I&rsquo;d like to engage in an exercise that&rsquo;s almost the reverse of that. Instead of imagining Hypothetical King in 2010, I&rsquo;m imagining a world in which today&rsquo;s tools exist in King&rsquo;s day. Specifically, I want to know what Dr. King would make of Twitter, the insistent social-media service that asks its users to describe &ldquo;What&rsquo;s happening?&rdquo; in 140 characters or less.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

        
  
          
  
         
  
      </div>

    

  </div>

